Raw dev notes -- Feb-March 2026

I've been working on a data project that needs clean article text from Israeli news
websites. Sounds simple, right? Just scrape the page and extract the article body.
Turns out, this is one of those problems that looks easy until you actually try it,
especially with Hebrew content.

I built a web service that now supports 17 Israeli news outlets -- major papers, news
sites, online-only publications. It's deployed on Google Cloud Run as a lightweight API.
But getting here was a journey.

Why Hebrew extraction is uniquely hard:
- Most off-the-shelf extraction libraries (newspaper3k, readability, etc.) are optimized
  for English. They make assumptions about text direction, paragraph structure, and
  character encoding that break with Hebrew.
- Israeli news sites use wildly different tech stacks. One uses DraftJS, another uses AMP,
  a third has a WordPress API, a fourth uses a custom CMS from the 2000s.
- RTL text handling adds complexity at every stage of the pipeline.
- Many sites have aggressive anti-automation measures. Some serve completely different
  content depending on who's asking.
- Several sites can't be reached reliably from cloud infrastructure at all.

I ended up building per-site extraction strategies with fallback chains. If the primary
CSS selector fails, try the next one. If that fails, try the site's API endpoint if it
has one. If THAT fails, try a generic extraction library as a last resort.

I did two full audit rounds across all 17 sites, testing with real articles. Found and
fixed extraction bugs affecting about half of them. The selectors drift over time as
sites update their markup.

The biggest lesson from this project: building a scraper is maybe 20% of the work.
Maintaining it is the other 80%. Every time a site redesigns or adds a new content
protection layer, it's a mini reverse-engineering project. I'm starting to think a
browser extension approach might be more sustainable long-term.

This is one of those projects where the interesting part isn't the code itself -- it's
the constant problem-solving. Every site teaches you something new about how the web
actually works behind the scenes.
